Given an array arr[] of integers of size n, for every element in the array, count the number of elements that are greater than it.

Examples: 
Input: arr[] = [4, 6, 2, 1, 8, 7] 
Output: [3, 2, 4, 5, 0, 1]

Input: arr[] = [2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8]
Output: [6, 5, 4, 3, 2, 1, 0]
 

Table of Content
[Naive Approach] Using Two Loops ‚Äì O(n^2) Time and O(1) Space
[Expected Approach 1] Using Hash Map - O(n log n) Time and O(n) Space
[Expected Approach 2] Using Sorting and Binary Search - O(n log n) Time and O(n) Space

-> [Naive Approach] Using Two Loops ‚Äì O(n2) Time and O(1) Space
  For each element in the array, we compare it with every other element and count how many elements are greater than it.

Since all comparisons are done directly without using extra data structures, this approach is simple but inefficient for large inputs due to its quadratic time complexity.

import java.util.ArrayList;
‚Äã
class Solution {
‚Äã
    static ArrayList<Integer> cntGreaterEle(int arr[], int n)
    {
        ArrayList<Integer> result = new ArrayList<>();
‚Äã
        // For each element, count elements greater than it
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            int cnt = 0;
‚Äã
            for (int j = 0; j < n; j++) {
                if (arr[j] > arr[i])
                    cnt++;
            }
‚Äã
            result.add(cnt);
        }
‚Äã
        return result;
    }
‚Äã
    // Driver code
    public static void main(String[] args)
    {
        int[] arr = {7, 9, 5, 2, 1, 3};
        int n = arr.length;
‚Äã
        ArrayList<Integer> ans = cntGreaterEle(arr, n);
‚Äã
        // Print result
        for (int x : ans)
            System.out.print(x + " ");
    }
}
