-> [Expected Approach 1] Using Hash Map - O(n log n) Time and O(n) Space
The main idea is to avoid comparing every element with all others.

  Instead we can count the frequency of each element using a hash map and process the elements in sorted order. 

By traversing the map from the largest element to the smallest, we maintain a running count of how many elements have already been processed. This running count represents the number of elements greater than the current element. The stored values are then used to directly output the result for each element in the original array.

import java.util.*;
‚Äã
class GfG {
‚Äã
    public static ArrayList<Integer> cntGreaterEle(int arr[])
    {
        int n = arr.length;
‚Äã
        TreeMap<Integer, Integer> mp =
                new TreeMap<Integer, Integer>(Collections.reverseOrder());
‚Äã
        // Store the frequency of the
        // array elements
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            mp.put(arr[i], mp.getOrDefault(arr[i], 0) + 1);
        }
‚Äã
        // Store the sum of frequency of elements
        // greater than the current element
        int x = 0;
        for (Map.Entry<Integer, Integer> e : mp.entrySet()) {
            int temp = e.getValue();
            mp.put(e.getKey(), x);
            x += temp;
        }
‚Äã
        ArrayList<Integer> result = new ArrayList<>();
‚Äã
        // Store result for each element in original array
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)
            result.add(mp.get(arr[i]));
‚Äã
        return result;
    }
‚Äã
    public static void main(String args[])
    {
        int arr[] = {7, 9, 5, 2, 1, 3};
‚Äã
        ArrayList<Integer> ans = cntGreaterEle(arr);
‚Äã
        // Print result
        for (int x : ans)
            System.out.print(x + " ");
    }
}
