-> [Expected Approach 2] Using Sorting and Binary Search - O(n log n) Time and O(n) Space
The idea is to determine how many elements are greater than each array element by leveraging sorting. A copy of the original array is first sorted in ascending order. In this sorted array, all elements greater than a given value appear after its last occurrence.
  Using upper_bound, we efficiently find the index of the first element that is strictly greater than the current value. 
Since the array is sorted, the number of elements greater than that value is simply the number of elements from this index to the end of the array, i.e., n ‚àí index.

import java.util.*;
‚Äã
class GfG {
‚Äã
    static ArrayList<Integer> cntGreaterEle(int arr[], int n)
    {
        int[] sorted = arr.clone();
        Arrays.sort(sorted);
‚Äã
        ArrayList<Integer> result = new ArrayList<>();
‚Äã
        // For each element, find count of elements greater than it
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            int idx = upperBound(sorted, arr[i]);
            result.add(n - idx);
        }
‚Äã
        return result;
    }
‚Äã
    // Custom upper_bound implementation
    static int upperBound(int[] arr, int target)
    {
        int low = 0, high = arr.length;
        while (low < high) {
            int mid = low + (high - low) / 2;
            if (arr[mid] <= target)
                low = mid + 1;
            else
                high = mid;
        }
        return low;
    }
‚Äã
    // Driver code
    public static void main(String[] args)
    {
        int arr[] = {7, 9, 5, 2, 1, 3};
        int n = arr.length;
‚Äã
        ArrayList<Integer> ans = cntGreaterEle(arr, n);
‚Äã
        for (int x : ans)
            System.out.print(x + " ");
    }
}
